<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-660-311  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 660 311.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  Dec 3 1990 v7 n48 p61(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>XVision lets Windows 3.0 PCs tap into X Window applications.andO;(Graphic Software Systems Inc.'s XVision 3.1) (productannouncement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Moser, Karen D.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Graphic Software Systems Inc. (Product introduction).andO;Product:   XVision 3.1 (Program development software) (Product introduction)Microsoft Windows 3.0 (Graphical user interface) (Computerprograms).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionUser Interface Management SystemsX Windows (Standard)Program Development ToolsUpgradingGraphical User Interface.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Karen D. MoserandM;Graphic Software Systems Inc.'s (GSS's) new XVision 3.1 upgrade aims tonarrow the gap between Windows 3.0-based PCs and Unix workstations andminicomputers running X Window applications.andM;With the revised software, users can create icons for X Window applicationsand load them into the Windows 3.0 program manager as a menu option, lettingthem be accessed as any standard Windows application, according to GSSofficials.andM;XVision 3.1 has been modified to provide better support for Windows 3.0 andto deliver a smoother interface between the two graphical user interfaces,the officials said.andM;&quot;Those that will benefit the most [from XVision 3.1] are firms that have alot of PCs with Windows 3.0 as a standard interface, but also want to accessX server [applications],&quot; said Jim Thomassen, technical marketing manager atGSS in Beaverton, Ore.andP;  GSS is an X terminal and graphics softwaredevelopment subsidiary of Spectragraphics Corp., a systems integrator in SanDiego.andM;XVision 3.1 furnishes support for a host of networks, allowing Windows 3.0users to conduct simultaneous links to a variety of X server applications,such as those running on Unix workstations and Digital Equipment Corp. (DEC)VAX/VMS minicomputers.andP;  It offers network support for Sun Microsystems Inc.'sPC/NFS, Ungermann-Bass Inc.'s Net/One, TCP/IP and Wollongong Group Inc.'sWIN/TCP for DOS.andM;The $449 package can be used with several X Window hardware platforms,including Hewlett-Packard Co.'s HP 9000, DEC's DECstation, Sun'sSPARCstations and IBM's RS/6000.andM;Registered users of XVision can upgrade to 3.1 for $150.andM;GSS can be reached at (503) 641-2200.andO;</TEXT></DOC>